---
import "../../styles/global.css";
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import DocTable from "../../components/docs/DocTable/DocTable.astro";
import Callout from "../../components/docs/Callout/Callout.astro";
import Screenshot from "../../components/docs/Screenshot/Screenshot.astro";

// Screenshot still to capture (shared Screenshot component):
// - The New Canvas (+) button in the editor tab bar.
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Canvas - Arris Docs"
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: "Docs", href: "/" }, { label: "Canvas" }]}
  heading="Canvas"
  lede="A board where you describe an analysis in plain English and an AI agent builds it: a query that runs, a chart of its results, and the text that explains them, all on one infinite canvas."
  tocItems={[
    { label: "Why use it", href: "#why" },
    { label: "Open a canvas", href: "#open" },
    { label: "Build with the agent", href: "#agent" },
    { label: "What you can place", href: "#objects" },
    { label: "Work on the board", href: "#board" },
    { label: "Saving", href: "#saving" },
  ]}
  currentPath="/canvas"
  prev={{ label: "Trino", href: "/supported-data-sources/trino", section: "Supported data sources" }}
  next={{ label: "Editor", href: "/querying/editor", section: "Querying" }}
>
  <h2 id="why">Why use it</h2>

  <p>
    A query tab answers one question and scrolls away. A canvas keeps the whole analysis in view:
    the SQL that pulls the data, the chart that makes it readable, and the notes that explain it,
    arranged side by side on an infinite board you pan and zoom.
  </p>

  <p>Reach for a canvas when you want to:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Go from a question to a chart fast</strong> &ndash; type "monthly sales by category" and let the agent write the query, build the chart, and run both.</li>
    <li><strong>Build a dashboard-style view</strong> &ndash; several queries, charts, and tables laid out together, refreshed on demand.</li>
    <li><strong>Explore step by step</strong> &ndash; chain one query off another's results, branch into variants, and annotate as you go.</li>
    <li><strong>Join across databases</strong> &ndash; put a query on each connection and reference them together.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="open">Open a canvas</h2>

  <p>
    Click <strong>New Canvas</strong> (the sparkles icon) in the editor tab bar, or run the
    <strong>New Canvas</strong> command from the keymap. It opens as a center tab you can rename,
    starting on the connection currently selected.
  </p>

  <p>
    The <strong>Connection</strong> picker at the top of the agent panel is a multi-select: add
    several connections and the agent reads every schema and can target each query at a different
    database. The first one picked is the default for queries you add by hand. The connection set is
    saved with the board.
  </p>

  <h2 id="agent">Build with the agent</h2>

  <p>
    The <strong>Agent</strong> panel runs down the left of the board. Describe what you want, for
    example <em>"monthly sales by category"</em>, and the agent reads your schema and replies with
    objects to add: usually a query that aggregates the data, a chart bound to it, and a one-line
    summary. Arris drops them on the board, runs the query, and renders the chart from the result.
  </p>

  <Screenshot
    src="/screenshots/canvas-board.png"
    alt="A canvas board with the Agent panel on the left, two query objects, a preview table, a line chart bound to a query, and a sticky note, with the chart properties panel open on the right."
    caption="A board the agent built and refined turn by turn: a query and its preview table, a chart re-pointed to a filtered query, and a sticky-note annotation."
  />

  <p>
    Pick <strong>Codex</strong> or <strong>Claude</strong> in the chat header (one shared preference
    with the SQL agent). Each turn also sees the current board, so follow-ups <strong>refine in
    place</strong> rather than only pile on: ask it to switch a chart to a line, set axis bounds,
    rewrite a query, retitle an object, move a query to another connection, or remove what you no
    longer need. Any query it adds or changes runs automatically, and bound charts and tables update.
  </p>

  <p>
    When what you ask for can come from a query already on the board, the agent
    <strong>builds on that result</strong>: it writes a query that selects <code>FROM</code> the
    existing cell, run in the in-memory engine, instead of hitting the database again. It only goes
    back to the database when no cell has the columns or grain it needs.
  </p>

  <Callout type="note" title="Your rows stay local">
    The agent runs the provider's local CLI in read-only mode and never touches your filesystem. It
    receives only your prompt, each connection's schema (as DDL and dialect), and a short summary of
    the objects already on the board, all size-capped. <strong>Row data is never sent.</strong> When
    the agent needs real rows, it posts a <strong>Share results</strong> card naming the queries it
    wants and why; nothing leaves until you click <strong>Share results</strong> (or
    <strong>Decline</strong>).
  </Callout>

  <p>
    Expand the collapsible <strong>Context</strong> section to preview the exact text handed to the
    agent: one labeled schema block per connection plus the board summary. The conversation is saved
    with the board, so reopening it restores the full history and the agent picks up where it left
    off. The <strong>Clear conversation</strong> button (the trash icon in the panel header) wipes
    the history and starts a fresh thread.
  </p>

  <h2 id="objects">What you can place</h2>

  <p>You can also build a board by hand. Every object is positioned and sized independently and may overlap.</p>

  <DocTable>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Object</th>
        <th>What it does</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Query</td>
        <td>
          One SQL statement with a <strong>Run</strong> button, in the same dialect-aware,
          schema-completing editor as the main SQL editor. The first run drops a preview
          <strong>table</strong> beside it. Reference another query by title with
          <code>FROM &lt;cell title&gt;</code> to chain off its result; upstream cells run first and a
          dependency arrow is drawn. (Joining a live table and another cell in one query is not yet
          supported &ndash; pull the live data into its own cell first.)
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Table</td>
        <td>Previews a query's rows as a scrollable grid, refreshed whenever that query runs.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Chart</td>
        <td>Visualizes a query's result with the same chart editor as the results viewer, refreshed whenever that query runs.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Text</td>
        <td>Headings and commentary. Double-click to edit in place.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Sticky note</td>
        <td>A coloured note for annotations, pinned on top.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Shape</td>
        <td>A rectangle, ellipse, or line for grouping. Rectangles and ellipses hold optional centered text; a rectangle's corners round by dragging its radius handle; a line can be solid, dashed, or dotted.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </DocTable>

  <h2 id="board">Work on the board</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Add</strong> from the toolbar at the bottom of the board. New objects land in your current view, never off-screen. Single-key shortcuts mirror the tools (<kbd>V</kbd> move, <kbd>H</kbd> hand, <kbd>/</kbd> SQL cell, <kbd>R</kbd>/<kbd>O</kbd>/<kbd>L</kbd> shapes); they fire only while the board is focused and are rebindable in Settings.</li>
    <li><strong>Select</strong> with a single click; <strong>move</strong> by dragging (objects may overlap); <strong>resize</strong> from any border or corner handle. Text and sticky notes open for editing on double-click.</li>
    <li><strong>Adjust properties</strong> in the right-hand panel: position, size, and a lock toggle for every object, plus per-kind controls (shape fill/stroke/radius, text font, sticky tint, a query's title and connection, a chart's source and full editor).</li>
    <li><strong>Relationship arrows</strong> draw themselves between a chart or table and its source query, or between chained queries, and re-route as you move objects. Right-click an arrow to delete it.</li>
    <li><strong>Copy, reorder, lock, delete</strong> from an object's right-click menu (Copy <kbd>⌘C</kbd> / Paste <kbd>⌘V</kbd>, restacking, lock, delete with <kbd>Delete</kbd>).</li>
    <li><strong>Run</strong> any query with its Run button, or <strong>Run all</strong> at the end of the toolbar to run every query at once (upstream cells first).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="saving">Saving</h2>

  <p>
    Boards save with your workspace, surviving a closed tab or an app restart. Closed boards appear
    in the <strong>Canvas</strong> section of the left sidebar; reopening one fits the view to its
    objects and restores the agent conversation. Query results are not saved &ndash; run the board's
    queries (or <strong>Run all</strong>) to refresh the data.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
